{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/100"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.04,0.1,0.54,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51256"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/100"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26498"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51256"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man is referred to the orthopaedic clinic with a two-year history of worsening left hip pain and stiffness, consistent with severe osteoarthritis. He is able to undertake all his usual activities, though has to take a break during his daily one-hour walk. His medical history includes hypertension, diabetes, episodes of unstable angina and a myocardial infarction nine months ago, which was treated with a drug-eluting stent (DES). He has been on aspirin and clopidogrel dual anti-platelet therapy (DAPT) and anti-hypertensive therapy since then for his ongoing cardiovascular risk management. He also takes paracetamol as required to manage his hip pain. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history. He is assessed as being a suitable candidate for a left total hip replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stop clopidogrel now and proceed to surgery in five days","Stop aspirin and proceed to surgery","Stop DAPT and proceed to surgery","Defer surgery for three months","Defer surgery for 18 months"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen considering elective non-cardiac surgery in patients with recent coronary stent placement, it is necessary to balance three key factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiovascular risk related to the stent and underlying cardiac condition\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe time sensitivity of the elective surgery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe bleeding risk from surgery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent evidence suggests that DAPT should be continued for 12 months after elective PCI and acute coronary syndrome (ACS) prior to elective surgery. For time-sensitive surgery, a minimum of 1 month of DAPT is required. However, for high-risk patients (those who have had a STEMI, NSTEMI, or high-risk stent procedure), DAPT should be given for at least 3 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient had a myocardial infarction treated with a drug-eluting stent (DES) nine months ago, which puts him at increased cardiovascular risk. The procedure itself is elective and non-urgent, as his osteoarthritis symptoms are not significantly impacting his daily activities. Total hip replacement is associated with a moderate bleeding risk. On the basis of these factors, the most appropriate option is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edefer surgery for three months\u003C/strong\u003E. This will allow the patient to complete a full 12 months of DAPT prior to the hip replacement, reducing his risk of stent thrombosis. Following this, his clopidogrel can be ceased and the hip replacement performed on aspirin monotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStopping clopidogrel now and proceeding to surgery in five days\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered in patients requiring more urgent intervention. However, given that his osteoarthritis is not life-threatening or majorly impacting his daily function, it would be more prudent to wait until the patient has completed 12 months of DAPT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStopping aspirin and proceeding to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Estopping DAPT and proceeding to surgery\u003C/strong\u003E are both contraindicated. Premature discontinuation of antiplatelet therapy, especially within the first year after DES placement, significantly increases the risk of stent thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeferring surgery for 18 months\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary in this case. While it would ensure completion of DAPT and allow for a period of single antiplatelet therapy, it delays a beneficial procedure longer than needed, potentially leading to further deterioration in the patient\u0027s quality of life due to hip pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, deferring surgery for three months strikes the best balance between minimizing cardiac risk and addressing the patient\u0027s orthopaedic needs in a timely manner. The decision to continue or discontinue antiplatelet therapy before surgery and the timing of procedures should be made on a case-by-case basis, considering the individual patient\u0027s risk factors and in consultation with the patient\u0027s cardiologist.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["12 months of DAPT is recommended post DES insertion, although shorter periods may be considered in patients requiring more urgent elective procedures.","Balancing the risk of stent thrombosis against the risk of surgical bleeding and the urgency of surgery is crucial when considering the timing of elective surgery after coronary stent placement."],"references":["2017 ESC focused update on dual antiplatelet therapy in coronary artery disease developed in collaboration with EACTS: The Task Force for dual antiplatelet therapy in coronary artery disease of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC) and of the European Association for Cardio-Thoracic Surgery (EACTS), European Heart Journal, Volume 39, Issue 3, 14 January 2018, Pages 213\u2013260, https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehx419","Extended Duration of Dual\u2010Antiplatelet Therapy After Percutaneous Coronary Intervention: How Long Is Too Long? https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/JAHA.119.012639","A. D. Oprea, W. M. Popescu, Perioperative management of antiplatelet therapy, BJA: British Journal of Anaesthesia, Volume 111, Issue suppl_1, December 2013, Pages i3\u2013i17, https://doi.org/10.1093/bja/aet402"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"100"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36537"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-23T10:54:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-23T10:55:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"100"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51256"}}},"meta":{"ca